## 3. The Two Orchestration Systems

Mike has **two orchestration systems** that coexist. Understanding which one handles which request is critical.

### 3.1 The Legacy Chat Orchestrator

**File:** `backend/src/lib/chatOrchestrator.ts` (4,145 lines)

This is the original system. It handles **real-time chat** — the conversational back-and-forth that most users experience. It is a single-agent system: one LLM call, one response, with tool-calling capabilities.

**When it handles requests:**

- Simple questions ("What is an NDA?")
- Template filling ("Fill in this contract template")
- When orchestration is disabled via environment variable (`PRISM_ORCHESTRATION_ENABLED=false`)
- When the user is in a direct chat (not project/workspace scope)
- When intent classification confidence is below 0.65
- As a **fallback** when the new orchestrator fails

**Key characteristics:**

- Single LLM turn with tool-calling loop
- Streams responses via SSE
- Has access to 50+ tools (document operations, search, email, workspace, etc.)
- Handles the Legal Safety Contract prepending
- Manages conversation history and context assembly

### 3.2 The New Multi-Agent Orchestrator

**File:** `backend/src/lib/orchestrator/index.ts` (488 lines)

This is the newer, more sophisticated system. It handles **complex legal tasks** that require multiple specialists working together. It decomposes requests into sub-tasks, runs them through specialized agents, validates the output, and synthesizes everything into one response.

**When it handles requests:**

- Classification is `complex` or `multi_agent` with confidence > 0.65
- User is in project or workspace scope (`routeMode === "project"` or `"workspace"`)
- Orchestration is explicitly enabled (`orchestrationEnabled: true`)

**Key characteristics:**

- Multi-agent pipeline with specialized agents
- Task planning with dependency resolution
- Self-critique and output validation
- Memory and learning system integration
- Rate limiting per user
- Automatic fallback to legacy on any failure

### 3.3 The Decision Flow

```typescript
// From orchestrator/index.ts
function shouldConsiderOrchestration(params): boolean {
  if (process.env.PRISM_ORCHESTRATION_ENABLED === "false") return false;
  if (params.orchestrationEnabled === false) return false;
  if (params.orchestrationEnabled === true) return true;
  return params.routeMode === "project" || params.routeMode === "workspace";
}
```

The orchestrator first checks if orchestration is even enabled. Then it runs intent classification. If the classification says "this is simple" or confidence is low, it falls back to legacy. Only when the stars align does the full multi-agent pipeline activate.

