## 15. Error Handling — When Things Go Wrong

### 15.1 LLM Failures

| Scenario | Handling |
|----------|----------|
| LLM call times out | `withTimeout()` rejects with descriptive error; falls back to legacy |
| LLM returns invalid JSON | Parser catches error; retry with validation error context; fallback plan |
| LLM returns schema-invalid plan | Zod validation catches error; retry once; fallback plan |
| Rate limit exceeded | Check before orchestration; fall back to legacy if exceeded |

### 15.2 Agent Failures

| Scenario | Handling |
|----------|----------|
| Agent times out (90s) | Mark task as failed; retry up to `maxRetries` times |
| Agent throws exception | Catch in `executeTask()`; mark as failed; retry |
| Critical task fails after retries | **Abort entire pipeline** immediately |
| Non-critical task fails | Continue with remaining tasks; note failure in results |

### 15.3 Pipeline-Level Fallback

The orchestrator has a **three-level fallback**:

```typescript
try {
  await this.runOrchestrated(params);
} catch (error) {
  // Level 1: Orchestration failed
  emitSse(write, { type: "orchestration_fallback", reason: error.message });
  try {
    // Level 2: Try legacy orchestrator
    const legacyResult = await this.legacy.handle({ ...params, skipUserPersistence: true });
    await legacyResult.stream(write);
  } catch (fallbackError) {
    // Level 3: Both failed
    emitSse(write, { type: "error", message: "Both orchestration and fallback failed." });
    write("data: [DONE]\n\n");
  }
}
```

### 15.4 Timeout Budgets

| Component | Timeout |
|-----------|---------|
| Total orchestration | 180 seconds |
| Task planning | 45 seconds |
| Agent execution (per agent) | 90 seconds |
| Response synthesis | 45 seconds |
| Self-critique | 8 seconds |

### 15.5 Rate Limiting

Orchestration has per-user rate limiting. If exceeded, the system silently falls back to the legacy chat path. The user sees no error — they just get a simpler response.

